             <div class="container" style="background:#f9f9f9; padding: 40px 20px; border-top: 1px dotted #999999;border-bottom: 1px dotted #999999;">
              <div class="row">
               <div class="col_12 omega" id="call-out-header">
                <p>
                 The
                 <strong>
                  Department of Linguistics
                 </strong>
                 , at Rice University's School of Social Sciences, is the home of an active community of scholars with a wide range of interests. Broadly defined, the department adopts a functional, usage-based approach to language and linguistic theory. A number of recurrent themes emerge in faculty research and the degree programs offered: in-depth investigation of languages, coupled with the search for cross-linguistic generalization; the effects of semantics, language-in-use, sociocultural factors, and other functional influences that motivate and constrain linguistic form; grounding of theories in solid empirical data of many sorts; an interest in the relation between language and mind; and interest in discourse and social/communicative interaction more generally.
                </p>
               </div>
              </div>
             </div>
             <p>
             </p>
